  1. We expect the carat of the diamonds to be strong correlated with the physical dimensions x, y and z. Use ggpairs() to investigate correlations between these four variables.
diamonds %>% 
  select(carat, x, y, z) %>% 
  ggpairs()

  1. So, we do find significant correlations. Let’s drop columns x, y and z from the dataset, in preparation to use only carat going forward.
diamonds_tidy <- diamonds %>% 
  select(-c("X1", "x", "y", "z"))

diamonds_tidy
ggpairs(diamonds_tidy)

  1. We are interested in developing a regression model for the price of a diamond in terms of the possible predictor variables in the dataset.
model <- lm(price ~ carat, data = diamonds)
model

Call:
lm(formula = price ~ carat, data = diamonds)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)        carat  
      -2256         7756
  1. ii Perform further ggplot visualisations of any significant correlations you find.
diamonds %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = price, y = carat)) +
  geom_point()

diamonds %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_boxplot()

diamonds %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = price, y = table)) +
  geom_point()

diamonds %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = price, y = depth)) +
  geom_point()

  1. Shortly we may try a regression fit using one or more of the categorical predictors cut, clarity and color, so let’s investigate these predictors:
diamonds_dummy <- diamonds %>% 
  dummy_cols(select_columns = c("cut", "clarity", "color"), remove_first_dummy = T) %>% 
  clean_names()
diamonds_dummy
  1. Going forward we’ll let R handle dummy variable creation for categorical predictors in regression fitting (remember lm() will generate the correct numbers of dummy levels automatically, absorbing one of the levels into the intercept as a reference level) First, we’ll start with simple linear regression. Regress price on carat and check the regression diagnostics.
lm(price ~ carat, data = diamonds)
